ReviewText: Shipped really fast.  I've had it about a month now and it is working perfectly.  Pay attention to what size your connection requirement is (width) - .187 or .250 inch.  This is 1/4 inch.

The vendor immediately phoned me, listened carefully to the problem, understood the problem (which is very rare today), and promptly mailed the correct fixtures to adapt the 3/8 #34; female lugs that are wired to my Conext Model Up 300 to the 1/4 #34; male lugs which are mounted to the battery.  I could not be happier.  I was made to feel super important.  And unlike practically all other vendors today - there was no attempt to blame it on me.  The response was  #34;all ears #34;, contained very little gratuitous back-chat, and resulted in immediate action.  My day was improved immensely by the way this vendor handled what was actually a very small problem that we could have let slide.  But the simple fact of the matter is that firm, clean, and snug electrical connections are at the heart of safe electronics.  It was indeed possible to make the wiring absolutely correct.  And the vendor made it so.  Yay for 1-800-battery!

This battery does not have F2 terminals. They are F1, and two small converters change the F1 to F2. One converted quickly and easily, the other took some work and pliers. I would have prefered a battery with F2 terminals as this one was described, as I specifically did NOT order a battery with converters. Be careful when you unwrap the package, the converters are small and just loose in the wrapping - took a while to find the second one.  But the battery fits and works well, just wish it was as described.

Looked far and wide for this battery as a replacement for a hand lantern. These are exact replacement batteries and fit the lantern. The price for two batteries and shipping was about the same as other vendors for just one battery and its shipping. Now I have a working lantern and a spare battery too.
I put this into a 1999 Mazda Miata MX-5.  It fit perfectly.  It came fully charged.  Delivered it saved me $50.  Great deal.  Love it.
Product was delivered on time, and works well with my Yamaha Vstar 1100CC. Fits right in had no issues starting.

works as advertised except for the narrower terminals...have had quantity 2 for over a year in different 750VA TripLite UPSs and both are working well. Tight to install in slots but they fit just like the original ones...will buy again. Delivery was good and on time.  I gave 1 less star because of the narrower terminals. ..just have to squeeze the terminals on the UPSs wire connectors to ensure a tight fit.
Nothing special about this one.  This item was purchased as a replacement for a home alarm system.  So far, it has solved the problem with the old battery going dead.
The acid delivery / installation system is well designed and simple to do.  This is my second one (4-wheeler, then bike).
Cheaper to order and install yourself instead of having security company do it!  Called security company and they were going to charge for battery, installing and making a trip to my house.
The battery came verry quick, looked and fit like the Harley battery without the Harley name. Cranked over just as good if not better than the original. I saved over 40.00 off the dealer price .

This product is priced good but for and stand up electric scooter the battery will not fit standard but with modifications that would range time and money than the battery may fit but would mess up that good deal you got on the batterywith adding on construction value.
slid these puppies in just like Prom night. I didn't even have to get the lube. it was just that easy.. My APC took it like a Tramp!
Functions as designed. i just wished the connector were not as flimsy. I had to modify the angle of the connectors so be careful when matching a replacement.

Purchased this because I read great reviews about this battery. And it may be great, but I never had a chance to find out because contrary to what I was told - this will not fit in a Honda 2003 Goldwing.
It was not the exact match. I had to rewire the battery in order to make it work. It was a toy for my Lil man. I am glad that I was able to to make it work.  But make sure you can iuse it.
Clips are nowhere near large enough to clamp on a battery. Would not big them again. Have to clip on edges of the terminals which is not idea a risks shorting out your vehicle
two different ends on cables. doesn't make sense. had to change the end on one side to fit it to the battery.

I needed a set of jumper cables for my new car and these had good reviews and were at a good price.  They have been used a few times already and do what they are supposed to - no complaints there.What I will say is that 12 feet really isn't an ideal length.  Sure, if you pull up front bumper to front bumper they are plenty long, but a lot of times you will be beside another car or can't get really close.  Because of this, I would recommend something a little longer than 12'.Great brand - get 16' version though.
When the product was being displayed and final purchase being made, there was no mention of it being a 12volt system only. I purchased it for a 24volt jeep and now its only a piece of junk for me.
The dimensions listed do not match those on the upg website. (Lower right hand side.) The height for this model (UTX9) is 4.13   not 3.86  . Hope this helps others. It almost got me. 2008 R6.

I bought this to replace my OEM terminal clamps.  This one did not fit at all on the negative battery terminal of a an Optima red top.  The clamp was way too big (like it was made for the positive terminal).  I sent it back to amazon for a refund.

I had bought some of the same gauge terminals from a local audio shop and wanted to save a few and found out these Picos actually have more copper but did make it a little more tough to use with my crimper...
Installed on camper and it installed with no problems. Package was easy to open. You do need some strength to push the center in.
I have even used this to start my dodge 2500 which has a heavy duty battery for starting and it worked great. The light pulls out to expose a 12v car adapter socket.

Work at a dealership, charged maybe once every month, clamps a little large   have to leave attached to battery on some vehicles for 30-45 seconds before it will jump off. Won't work on some newer vehicles with high CCA rated batteries, but, when it won't, have yet to borrow someone's that will. Small, lightweight and value cannot be beaten.

I have used my jump-n-carry to jump my car twice this last month during cold weather and even helped to jump start a friends moped. I plugged it back in after each use and it was at full charge after 20 minutes or so. Worked wonderfully every time!Really nice and compact. Solid feel and build. Couldn't be happier with my purchase.
Perfect Fit - Ideal for when you don't need to replace an otherwise good OEM axle. Fits all FWD/AWD Volvo 850   S/V70 '93-'00

I've learned my lesson to just stick with OEM parts for replacements. This wheel bearing for my wifes '05 Saturn Ion 2 was no exception. As usual, the descriptions from ACDelco weren't that great, and I wasn't sure if it should get the bearing with or without the abs sensor. Glad I got the one with the sensor. When I removed the old bearing, the old sensor stuck in the knuckle, and was all gunked up. Popped the old sensor out, cleaned everything up, lubed with never seize, and reassembled. Worked perfect.

I installed this hub.  It turned off my service traction control light, and abs light.  I thought all was good until the bearing starting squealing on the way to the alignment shop.  I torqued the bolts to specs.  I installed a new hub bearing from autozone.  It is having the same problem.  It seems that it wasn't the cause.

Defies logic.  Nothing in the ad says they will ship 3 so I ordered two thinking there was one in a box.  Now I have 6 total.  I can't imagine why there would be three.  Two would make some sense.Other than that they are dust caps.  They go round and round with the rotor.  They keep the dust out and the grease in.  Pretty functional overall.

Surprisingly the product was exactly what was shown. I was worried it wouldn't line up right but they are in and working. I can't say how long they will last but even if it only works for 2 years the savings was worth it.
I received the part in good shape in a fast and efficient manner. The quality of a Timken bearing was just what I expected.

this is a good part. autozone/advanced auto priced the wheel bearing alone at over 150 dollars for a chevy cobalt.. plus would have had to pay the labor.. hub and wheel bearing is easier to install and the price on this was over a hundred dollars cheaper!! i rate this 5 stars for sure!!

I installed this part on my 2001 Honda Odyssey about a year ago, and it's been working great ever since. The one on the other side is now failing, so I'll be ordering another to complete the pair. The fit and finish were perfect, and it went in without any problems.Update: Side #2 is now installed and working great. With regard to the other reviewer, he could have a point. My van, though, has rear drum brakes, so had no need of holes to hold the rotor in place.For safety, be sure to replace the spindle nut every time, per Honda's factory service manual.
These are a perfect fit and work great. Easy to install and seem to be durable, only time will tell.These not only fixed the abs issue,but the car ride so much better!
No install issues. Works as it should. Let's see how long it lasts. That will be the biggest part of it.

I just installed these bearings. They were  #34;snug #34; but fit well. The retaining bolts that hold them were a challenge these are on the backing plate (nothing to do with the new bearings). Make sure you put WD-40 or something like it on the center bolts and the nuts that hold the plate. Made a difference on the car's handling, much tighter (96k on Buick Park Ave). Oh yes, and make sure you tighten the center nut (this one must be really tight). You have to re-use yours, no new one is included, and of course the instructions say to  #34;replace the center hub nut #34;. I tried to buy them locally, and no one has them in stock, you get a new one if you order the whole hub assembly. These bearings from Timkin are the way to go, spend the extra for these so hopefully you don't get to do it again anytime soon.If you don't have a lift rack (I don't) figure about 2 hours a side. After you complete the first one, you will probably improve by 25%.
It fit perfectly and installed easily for this back yard mechanic on my 2005 Silverado.  It took be about an hour and a half.

The bearing seems to fit and function properly. the install was simple I would advise a 2 arm puller on the next attempt. only because of heat and corrosion due to the failed bearing. It was removed in to 2 pieces. It was overdue for replacement.  Seems to be a direct fit replacement part. If any Issues will be in contact in the future. SINCERLY JOHN DOM.
Fit and installed fine.Has been driven 100 miles a day for two weeks with no problem.  Now we will see how long it lasts!

The switch I received was great, it works fine. The problem is the listing shows 3 switches, indicates plural in the description yet I only received one switch. A bigger issue is that the listing shows two different switches. Fortunately I needed the one they did send. I contacted the seller and was told that it is just the was the ad runs but it is only for one switch (the one I received). I suggested they correct the ad but it still shows the three switches. The listing is very misleading.
I only rated a 4 because it is working perfectly now but time will tell on a converter. It performs well. Just as it is suppose too. Would definitely recommend and buy again! So far so good!
Always liked brand, fit like it was supposed to, timken has always been my go to bearing. Would buy again
Too tight. You'll have to modify this cap to get it on. I gave up and put the 45 year old caps back on. Good thing I have get looking after market wheels that don't show the cap.

Easy installation. Just splitting the transfer case where it sits. The front drive shaft doesn't need to be removed to replace the chain. The parts are of good quality as always from Crown Automotive. Do not use ATF in the transfer. Mopar has special oil for this purpose.
Good value. Very pleased. Recommend this belt.I used it for the A/C belt on my 2002 BMW 540. Correct fit.
worked well until the truck sold. I would buy another one without question quiet like OEM piece of course easy install with the correct tools.
I bought this and a bunch of other Gates products for my Honda Ridgeline Timing belt / Water Pump / Serp Belt project.  Items are new and fit well.
No squeak issues, tough belt and easy to handle. Couldn't hope for anything more, does what it's made to :)

Got it fast...and had no issues with install, fit perfect on my 02 civic ex. Other sites wanted double for the same item.  Definitely would recommend.
This serpentine belt fix with my car,and made from USA,good quality as I expected,I will order some to spair for my cars.
Look solid, felt solid and fit perfectly with no issues. Installation can be confusing. Study old belt configuration before removing.

The description says this belt contains only two grooves, but believe me - you'll be grooving every time you drive. Yes, it's a touch pricey, but every time you drive to your bankruptcy lawyer's office, you'll feel where the extra three million dollars was spent. Don't get caught off guard. Be sure to buy a spare.
I put this belt in my Roadmaster, putting the belt was super easy, and is much quite than the one I used to have. Recommended.
This belt had a drastic sound difference from the previous.  Good quality and easy installation.  Highly recommended.  I will be using one on my truck.
Works perfectly.  Followed many other G8 owners, and killed of the squeak my car developed around 56k.  Perfect fit, seems high quality.
This is a great buy.  Quality is great and so were the specs.  It fit like a glove without any complications.  Gates is a quality product.  Shipping was fast.
A well made belt. Not much else to say. OEM replacement on a 30 year old aircraft tug. Looks like this one will do another 30 no problem.
The ACTUAL pitch, in inches, is .0921, not .092.  Thus, it will not fit the flywheel of the Spacetronics InfiniteImprobabilty Drive.
It came in fast. The intake hose was a direct fit so no mod's were needed.Very easy to install and nice quility.
Great product.  Fits perfect on my 99 Camry 2.2 the price is great I was quoted twice as much as this one cost at the auto parts store.

It arrives twisted and tied into a knot tighter than the picture shows, no new copper seal washer.  Because it's wound up so tight, probably straight off the assembly line, it's difficult to use.  You have to grab it, untwist it, push on, lube, pull off, then it springs back into a little coil flinging grease all over the place.  Everything I've tried to get it to straighten out doesn't work.  Since you don't get a new copper seal, it leaks there, more grease all over the place.1224 is 24   long, 1230 30  , 1236 36  , 1218 18  .UPDATE:  Fastforward 5 years later, I tried again and ordered another one.  If anything, this one is even worse.  It arrives tied in such a tight knot its like a spring.  This time rather than trying to use it, I returned it.  I'll end up going to my local hose maker to have a custom one made.

I had read other reviews about the plastic fittings offered by other vendors and to stay away.  When I removed the leaking elbows from the engine I understood why.  Each one snapped off exactly where the O-ring sits.  If you are looking for a short term repair spend a couple dollars less and buy plastic.  If you want to do the job right, buy these aluminum elbows which are unaffected by coolant and the temperature fluctuations of your engine.Simply remove the old elbows which WILL break off, use a small hooked tool (O-ring remover, bent wire, etc) to pull out the small broken plastic pieces, use a round wire brush (similar to one you would use to clean copper pipe prior to soldering) available in the plumbing department to clean out the openings and slip the new aluminum fittings in.  You know have a repair that will outlast the engine.These fittings are ready to go complete with new O-Rings and you cannot beat the price.

Ran the item number after I found the part at an online auto supplier. Amazon says it didn't fit my car but I took a chance that the part number was right. It arrived super fast thanks to Amazon Prime. I saved about 45% over what the parts house wanted so it was a good deal all the way around.

E46 bmw 330ci. Factory hoses crack and had to replace, saw this price and brought it. worked great once you get it in. It take great afford to take the old hose out and putting this one in but after that, bleed it and should be good to go. recommend taking it to a mechanic to put it in but if you have helper around, and that you are pretty strong then do it yourself.

I hate using after-market parts on my vehicles as they are usually Chinese junk. These are the same OEM ford parts that you buy at the dealer for twice the price. In this case, this hose is an excellent fit and does not leak, just as you expect from an OEM hose! I expect it will outlive my truck.
This was a perfect fit and saved us a lot of money! Came with all of the connectors needed too!
Very nice, it fit perfect in my jeep laredo 2000, thanks!!Very nice, it fit perfect in my jeep laredo 2000, thanks!!
MOLDED COOLANT HOSE - PREFERRED HOSE - UPPER HOSE ROUTES AROUND SERPENTINE BELT  Fits 2001 F-250 Super Duty 7.3 PSD and eliminates the need to remove upper hose to remove the serpentine belt.

Got one of these from Dorman for my 2000 Ford Taurus LX Flex Fuel and it leaked in   exactly   the same spot the broken one did.  Contacted the nice folks at Dorman and they sent me out a replacement. They actually give a darn about their customers!Unfortunately, the replacement was even worse and the hose came apart at exactly the same spot! The nice Dorman representative was apologetic and actually got me an OEM part that was a perfect fit and, drum roll please, did NOT leak!Not sure if Dorman will recall the ones at Amazon, but they are dedicated to standing behind their products and to provide inexpensive but functional replacement products. This problem occurred around November of 2011, in case you're reading this sometime in the future and the problem with the hoses will surely have been remedied.

This thing is great. Allows you get to all the goodies without being in park. It has the additional benefit of not having to tap into your wiring harness unless you are putting a backup camera in. It scared the crap out of me the thought of noodling with that to make my radio work.

The ACDelco 25528382 Pressure Accumulator is an exact replacement for the original Buick Reatta accumulators. Installation is as simple as installing an oil filter. It stopped the red brake warning light from flashing each time I hit the brakes. I bought my accumulator from The Reatta Store ( [...] ) but it was sold and shipped by Amazon. I even got free shipping!

Take a look.  The bolts are too long and are minimum grade steel.  Even after a short tow, the clamp is too loose to provide stabilization.  I had to re-engineer the bolts with shorter case-hardened bolts, nuts and lock washers.  That helped but the frame is obviously mild steel which stretches and flattens, so I still had to re-tighten them after a 5-hour highway tow.I am now shopping for something better.  Wouldn't buy them again.
Same as original equipment for my 2006 Honda Civic. Perfect fit, even includes brake lubricant. Quiet and smooth even on the original rotors, just like new. Highly recommended.

2005 Odyssey, New Front rotors and pads are a piece of cake.These pads are great, they grab well, last well, and don't squeak or squeal.Bonus#1 - This package came with new clips, which my previous pads did not include.Bonus#2 - The price was cheaper than at the auto parts stores, even with coupons or rebates.When it's time to do brakes, I always replace the pads and rotors, for less than a mechanic would charge for just the pads.Change them a little bit early, before other parts start to fail; then it's an easy DIY job.
Heavy duty and smooth locking action. And very reasonably priced. If you are looking for a nice, basic lock for your bike, this is it.

I used to use Toyota OEM pads,  because I'm very conscious about safety and hate the squeaking noise after 10k miles. I had Akebono pads on my 2007 camry. I've put more than 30k on it, there still plenty of pads left on it. I think I can put at least another 15-20k before the next brake service. If you are planning to go off-label and apply it to the sump of a 4-cylinder Lycoming, be advised that you will want at least the next size up. I bought this for a 2002 Honda Odyssey. Let me tell you that Amazon parts will check this saying that it will not fit my 2002 Honda Odyssey. If I were you, I will go to the Akebono website directly and search your car model for the right parts. I did this to make sure the pads I buy from Amazon works. I got it installed and everything works great. No noise, squeaks or anything. Just to let everyone know that Akebono manufacture also manufacture the OEM parts for my 2002 Honda Odyssey. When I took the old pads out, and look at the back, there is a serial number that starts with   AK   referring to this break pad. My Odyssey is 90,000 miles and never had a brake change before so it still had the old original. So this pad may be better or the same as OEM. Also to let everyone know this is manufactured in the USA. Says so on the box, so it is quality brand I will trust for now on. I used Duralast brakes for my other vehicles from Autozone, and they were not good. I will buy this brand for now on on all my vehicles. This brake pad is for the front.

So far I have about 800 miles on them. They make some noise but I don't think they are fully broken in yet.Its disappointing not getting the product I was expecting. Someone please fix the picture.

Fit like a glove. Or on an FJ Cruiser, more like an awkward metal glove with pins, but you get the idea.Just like the factory ones, shim and pins included.

It is a crime the way car dealers and some brake shops rip people off for simple repairs. I have no problem with them making a buck, but marking labor and parts up 400% is just not right. How many naive drivers are throwing money away every day because they do not realize how simple and inexpensive brake work is. If I would have had the time, I would have installed them myself. Fits the sedona 2002. And shipped fast. I installed them myself. Never did before. Googled how to first and installed with no problem

Bought this to change the front brakes on my 2005 VW Jetta. Never had used one before and had it figured out in a couple minutes, very solid construction, good quality metal. First piston I tried to compress took some effort but the tool never skipped a beat, didn't slip or falter. Second piston squeezed in like a breeze. Why mess around with C clamps when you can pick this wonderful tool up for $35~ and not damage your car or hands! Looked at cheaper products but leary of cheap knobs breaking off, this tool is all steel, and the high quality handle should last me a lifetime of home brake changes. Paid for itself in the first job.

I'm going to purchase this tool because I needed it yesterday. I've never had to deal with these type of brake calipers in the past and was at a loss when my C-clamp wouldn't compress the caliper in. My local Hyundai dealer called me about my other vehicle that was in the shop for more serious repair when I told him I was working on my other Hyundai and couldn't get the rear calipers compressed. He was happy to tell me how to use a pair of needle nose pliers to help screw them in. I will say it was so difficult to keep the pliers spread apart to fit the slots and I kept loosing my grip. It was so frustrating and I ended up adding a couple objects (washers) in between the handle to keep it from closing and then securing the object in place with a rubber band. This made it easy to use the pliers without fumbling them. I did have to take off the bleeder valve cover on the caliper and the reservoir cover to allow it to screw in easily and even had to back it out a couple times to get them to screw all the way in. Not sure why I had to screw them OUT to get them IN but it worked. Anyway, after dealing with that I decided that I will be purchasing a tool next time to make it easier and I think this tool will do the trick. I don't really care if it's precision made like another commenter said it needed to be. Hey, as long as it makes it easy to wind them back in right? If my needle nose pliers can get them in why wouldn't these tools?Here is what my caliper looks like [...]

Pros - Good stainless construction.  Stainless banjo fittings and the kit comes with all new hardware. The Line is of high quality and the length is correct. My only issue is with the brass fitting that mates the hose to the brake line in the vehicle. If you are not careful, it is very easy to strip. And it has to be zip tied or otherwise tied to the bracket in the vehicle. That looses points in my book. I think Skyjacker could do better on this one.
Got this to replace a worn one on a 2006 G-6. Fit was perfect. I have found that most items from Dorman HELP are good OEM replacements.

I purchased both the large and small universal adapters in order to bleed my S2000s brake and clutch master cylinders.  At first look after I initially received both items - I thought there was a mistake due to the fact they looked to be the same size.  I considered returning the large adapter due to the fact the small adapter's diameter very close to the large - and was more than big enough for my brake master cylinder.  In fact - the small adapter was almost too big for my clutch master cylinder.  This is when the biggest design flaw of the small adapter became clear - the seal does little to prevent leaks.The seal design of the small adapter is inferior when compared to the large adapter (flat seal vs a slightly conical seal on the large adapter).  The difference was not clear until I tried to bleed my brakes with the small adapter and fluid leaked out everywhere - with the adapter properly clamped down - and reset several times, and eventually clamped down as tight as it could be clamped.  The result was the same (on both the brake and clutch master cylinder) - severe leaks and a horrible mess.  And may I remind everyone that brake fluid is not the kind of substance you want leaked - least of all on a painted surface.The other unfortunate flaw with the adapter I received is one of the screw-down posts (threaded post that links to the chain) would not thread into the knurled knob due to the threads being stretched.  Fortunately, my purchase of the large adapter gave me a working set.I am not happy with this purchase and do not recommend it.  The large adapter still leaked slightly, but at a much more manageable rate and is suitable for the Honda S2000 brake master cylinder.  The large adapter is too large for the clutch master cylinder.

Extremely fast shipping and email response.  Item is small and does exactly what it says in the description.  Easy to install and directions are clear.  Installed in a 05 explorer with a pioneer avh-p1400dvd and it works seamlessly!  I would refer this to anybody!
works great fast shipping! the install couldn't be easier. small and compact. read instructions and its a easy install less than 2 minutes

Overall, this kit worked for my 2004 Toyota Sequoia. All of the springs and hold-down parts seemed to be an exact match of what I had on my car. However, for some reason it seems that they skimped on the adjuster. There are three parts to the adjuster -- the star adjuster itself, the screw-in saddle, and the saddle with a stud. The stud was way too short, maybe 1/4 inch, and was very hard to hold into place when trying to place the adjuster between the brake shoes. After wrestling with it for 10 minutes, I just decided to pitch it and reuse the one that was already there. The stud on that one was about 1/2 inch, and was plenty long to keep it in place. Like other's have stated, this Stant #10504Y (Yellow) locking Gas Cap did not come up as compatible with my vehicle, but the Stant #10504 (Black) Gas Cap did show compatible.  I figured that Stant used the same part number with the (Y) to designate the Yellow E-85 Locking Gas Cap.  So I ordered the yellow cap as my Terrain came with an original Yellow Gas cap since it can use E-85.  I have never put E-85 in my vehicle, but wanted to keep things a near as original as possible.  I have had the locking Gas cap on for 5 days now and NO check engine light has come on what so ever driving the vehicle every day now. I have even put gas in the vehicle since installing the locking cap.  Like other's have mentioned, it would have been nice to have some sort of lanyard attached to the locking cap, like my original one did, but every vehicle uses different methods for attacking the lanyard and it would be difficult for the manufacture to come up with a universal way of securing the lanyard to the vehicle gas door.  It would have been nice if the gas cap had some sort of eyelet that a lanyard could be threaded through.  I have a great lanyard from one of my iPad stylus pens I don't use that would be perfect for attacking to the gas door and the gas cap if there was a eyelet to secure the lanyard to.  I'm sure not going to drill a hole in the gas cap to thread the lanyard through.  To me this isn't a end of the world issue so I am NOT downgrading the rating because there was no lanyard.  If you look at all the locking gas caps, here on Amazon, you won't find but one or two that have a lanyard.  Maybe someday the manufactures come up with a good universal way to secure a lanyard to the vehicle gas door.  So for now I am pleased with my purchase.

As far as overflow bottle caps go, this one is one of the better built in a sea of copycat units.  Mine was built in Germany, but your mileage may vary.  The cheap China-built units, that are basically thrown in with the overflow bottle replacement kits, look identical from the outside, but are assembled different.  This cap will not fall apart after a few heatings and coolings in your Jeep Cherokee vehicle.  It is rated to factory 16-pounds, and you must not be tempted to use a Volvo 22 pound substitute cap instead.  Yes, those caps are superior strength in design, but the extra pressure will encourage your engine to blow out the hoses during a hot drive, and that is a catastrophic failure, not merely an annoying leak at the overflow bottle that you can wait out at the side of the road.  Suggestion:  Due to a design flaw in Jeep Cherokee overflow bottle design, WRAP your T-35  #34;Radiator #34; Cap with three heavy duty tie wraps with the binding heads separated by 120 degrees in a circle.  Or, buy an inexpensive, stainless steel 2.25 #34;-4 #34; range hose clamp and wrap that around the center of the T-35.  That will prevent radiator fluid steam heat from damaging and distorting the cap over time.  Future leaking and replacements averted!

Back in October of 2012 I knocked out my ambient temp sensor on my '00 528i while driving over a piece of tire on the highway on my way to work, and although I did not know what had happened that morning I figured it out on my way home that same day when the heat really kicked in and my A/C did not work.  Needless to say I was skeptical about buying this item as with most things I suppose, you really need to just stop overthinking things and decide what you want to do.  After seeing several reviews and posts on internet forums I decided to purchase this as the Texas heat was really beginning to take its toll on me.  I am the type of person that will not even change my own oil, I'll take it to the shop but usually by the time I get off work every shop is closed and besides I figured I had to get my hands dirty at some point.  I went back and looked at the forums one last time, went outside armed with only a pair of wire cutters, my socket set to disconnect the battery lead as I wasn #8217;t sure what kind of damage I was potentially looking at from my lack of experience and electrical tape of course.  Approximately 10 minutes later, I taped up the wires and repositioned the sensor so it was out of harm #8217;s way and connected the battery lead back on and I fired up my car with the very missed +96 on my display instead of -40 and cold air for the first time in almost 9 months.  This was probably as hands on as I have gotten other than replacing my own headlights not too long ago, and this is enough for a while.  A product that is packaged and includes all items as advertised, does what it is supposed to do, and relatively easy to install even for a person with no experience.  AWESOME!

As other reviewers have mentioned, this unit does not come with any mounting bolts, and the ones that come out of the compressor are about 4 inches too long, for this part. It would be nice if they included some notes, indicating which size bolts you need, instead of trying to take the stock compressor bolts and match them up, to what you think will be the right length.The other issue is with the power steering pump, filler neck. In my 97 Blazer, there is a mounting tab, welded on to the power steering neck. This mounting tab is secured by a small bolt, that was attached to the original compressor. When you get this pulley bypass plate, it does not have a hole, to mount this filler neck to, so you are left with sandwiching the filler neck, mounting plate, in between the bottom of the pulley plate, and the top of the existing compressor bracket. Not sure why this was never accounted for, when this part was made.

Installation was relatively easy, especially considering I am not a   car guy   at all. It took me about an hour but, again, I have no experience working on engines, etc. other than to change the oil and simple maintenance-type jobs. Even a semi-experienced person could probably have the old intake out and the new one installed in about 20 minutes. With a small socket set, a screwdriver and/or a cordless drill, this can be done with little or no problems. The one suggestion I would make to people installing this (or if I had it to do over again) is that I would go ahead and attach the breather hose to the Volant vent BEFORE the vent is installed, as it is a very snug fit and can be a little awkward to fit on once the vent is installed. Everything else was a piece of cake.I read some reviews that the Volant instructions weren't very good but I found them to be very clear and concise (although, b/c of my ignorance, I had to search online to make sure I was unscrewing the MAF sensor and not something else)...Packaging and shipping were great (I got mine in 2 days for free with my Amazon Prime membership).Now, the results...it definitely makes acceleration a little   throatier   than before but it's not obnoxious. I was worried that my truck might sound like a Harley with the new intake but that's not the case. It is a bit louder at the top end of acceleration than I planned for but, even still, not obnoxious. It sounds tough. My truck now has a noticeable increase in acceleration, which is what I bought it for. It's too early to tell the impact, if any, on gas mileage but I've read and heard consistently that it will give you an extra 1-1/2-3 MPG increase, which is always nice. Would definitely recommend.

I specifically ordered this  #34;Anchor #34; brand mount based on positive feedback on the Piloteers forum. After initially panicking, I was scheduled to install the next day, I contacted Anchor and confirmed that these were indeed rebranded Anchor motor mounts.  As for the quality, fit and finish - The fit was good and they installed with little difficulty.  The quality appeared to be similar to the original equipment although, I noticed some defects in the paint which already had signs of rust.  Not perfect but, I received them quickly due to Prime and saved a ton of $ over the cost of the Honda original equipment replacement.  I replaced the passenger side mount at the same time and my review for that mount is exactly the same as this.  Tip: If you decide to DIY the motor mounts on your Pilot / Ridgeline or Passport, make sure you are prepared to replace all of the small plastic molding clips that hold on the splash shield under the front bumper.  The small ones are brittle and are not designed to be removed and reinstalled.  order a pack of these: http://www.amazon.com/Push-type-Fastener-91503-SZ3-003-Element-Ridgeline/dp/B00842A7F4/ref=sr_1_3?s=automotive ie=UTF8 qid=1395075816 sr=1-3 keywords=91512-sx0-003.  You'll only need about 14 or so but, they are cheaper in bulk.  There are 3 or 4 larger clips which you might be able to carefully removed without breaking but, mine were brittle and I cracked a couple of them.  The Honda part number is 91503-sz5-003.  Good luck!

Chrome Valve Cover - The Amazon site stated that the Chrome Valve Cover would fit my 225 slant six engine.  It fits, but is not a stock application.  This valve cover only has two holes, the stock valve cover has three holes...1 for the oil cap, 1 for the breather cap, and 1 for the pcv valve.  If I use the chrome valve cover I cannot use the stock breather cap, and must use an after market push-on cap in order to have an access hole to put in oil.  Using this type of breather cap reqiuires either plugging the line from the air cleaner or purchasing an after-market custom air cleaner that also won't support the stock fresh air intake.  Unless you are willing to make several custom alterations, I suggest staying with a stock valve cover.  One other thing, the two holes in the chrome valve cover aren't the same size as the ones in the stock valve cover, so plan to buy new grommets also.

Bought this filter before reading the commentary on the web.  Had always thought Fram was a reliable brand made by a division of the Honeywell Corporation, but numerous questions raised by bloggers.  Turns out Honeywell sold the division to an Australian company in 2011, and the quality does seem questionable.  After splitting off the can top from the filter base, I found the filter media to have the manufacturing flaws noted in the blogs.  There was a large gap where the paper media was supposed to be joined around the steel core, and the end-caps were indeed made of loose-fitting cardboard.  Now more curious, I bought another model number at a local auto parts (PH3569) and opened it.  This filter was very well made with a tight, dense, even fitting media and steel end-caps.  If you use a lot of filters and can get a good price on Fram, you might open and examine the type you use to see if it's the better quality.  Hopefully, Fram is making the effort to improve all the types, regardless of where they are manufactured/sourced.

This tool works, but I found it a bit clumsy.  It is two bits in one.  A slot bit, which fits the recessed Quadrajet idle mixture screws.  the other end is an open hex socket for the other type of mixture screw.  At the back of each socket is a square base that fits up into a small rubber handle.  You push the end you are not going to use up inside of this rubber handle and the square base fits in so when you turn the handle the tool turns.  This square base barely fits into the handle and is loose and kept falling out.  Right when you are concentrating on how many turns you find you are not turning the tool at all because this tool has fallen out of the handle.  It only falls out far enough to stop turning.  the tool but if you don't see this and keep turning the handle, as the very end of the tool stays in but with not grip so you are turning nothing but the handle.  I finally discarded the handle and just used my fingers to turn the square base, or knob, that is attached to the socket.  The shaft is a flex cable, which makes it nice for tight places or reverse work like I had to do, as this was a motorhome so I had to work on the adjustments from the rear of the carb.  It worked but the handle was a joke.  I could have used some electrician tape and solved the problem.  It is a small tool, the socket ends about a 1/4 #34; dia.  the square bases about 3/8 #34; and the 2.5 inch foam, rubber type handle about 1/2 #34; dia.  May 7 #34; - 8 #34; in length.  The flex shaft is about 1/8 #34; dia.  Easy to store or lose.  .This is an expensive tool, for what you get but it is one of those  #34;must have #34; tools to get at those recessed mixture screws.  I have heard of others taking a piece of steel brake line (thin walled metal tubing) and flattening one end just enough to slip over the mixture screw, and the tubing being just small enough in dia. to fit into the recess. Too late for me but maybe not for you.

I don't know how much more involved pulling the fuel pump from the original housing would have been, but replacing the entire housing with the fuel pump already installed sure did make this an easy 'pull-and-drop' installation. ** UPDATE: See below **The reason I changed the entire housing is because I have an 04 Sentra SE-R Spec V and there was a Nissan service bulletin (NTB05-052a) which was a fuel-pump repair kit. The repair kit itself was over $200 from the dealer, plus my fuel pump was not maintaining adequate pressure, so not only was this easier to install, but also saved me quite a bit of money as well.I didn't want to install the Nissan-branded fuel pump because it is known to have issues and need replacing every ~60K miles. I went with Bosch for ease of installation and company reputation.I recommend this kit if you have an 04-06 Sentra and have been plagued with any kind of hard-starting issue and/or fuel pressure issue that might be observed by a drop in engine RPMs.** UPDATE: you will have to do a bit of wiring since the new fuel pump housing does NOT include the Fuel Temperature Sensor, although it is shown in the picture (at the very bottom of the fuel pump housing (Blue and Black wires). The housing comes bare and also with no instructions! It's definitely misleading since the picture clearly shows the Temperature sensor in-place. If you're getting the P0183 after installation, this is your issue. Transfer the Fuel Temp Sensor over from your old Fuel Pump housing and your code should be cleared and not return. I threw my old housing away too soon and had to pick up the part from the Junk Yard-- 35 miles away! Hard lesson learned.*** 2nd UPDATE: I contacted Bosch AutoPart Customer Service and was able to talk with a Bosch parts specialist: The Bosch 69701 Electric Fuel pump does NOT have support for CA emissions, hence the lack of Fuel Tank Temp Sensor. The 69701 is only made for Federal Emissions vehicles. Therefore Bosch does not supply the Fuel Tank Temperature Sensor and 69701 is actually not compatible with my 04 Sentra SE-R Spec V.

I received this antenna as a gift, so I didn't personally purchase this through Amazon.Installation is really easy after you do all the necessary cleaning and prep (alcohol wipe down to remove the wax).1. Just unscrew the original antenna off the mount.2. Tape the alignment guide on your car.3. Attach the helix wire with the provided screw.4. Remove the cover of the 3M double sided tape and place the shark fin (Beat-Sonic calls it a Dolphin antenna) cover down over the factory antenna base and between the cutout in the alignment guide and press down to make the cover stick on your roof.Simple as that.  It took me about 10 minutes.It's painted to match the original color of your car so the installation looks factory and cool.  But.......you do lose some antenna gain.  I tuned onto popular local AM stations (for those of you in the Los Angeles area, the stations I used were KNX 1070 and 790 KABC) during installation.  When I made the connection as described in step 3 above, the radio reception was just as good as the factory antenna.  This was a dry test fit, so I didn't remove the cover of the double sided tape.  As I was lowering the fin cover over the factory base (step 4) I started to lose the signal (more static).  I removed my hand just to make sure my body wasn't blocking any of the signal, but no improvement.  I lifted the fin cover off and the signal came back.  Bottom line, the shark fin cover is not totally RF transparent and you are going to lose signal.If you live in a major city, this may not be an issue.  If you're far from the city and constantly struggling to get an AM signal, then I would not recommend this antenna.If I were to rate this on a scale from 1 to 10: Installation - 10; cool factor - 10; Performance - 7

I was having trouble with (2005 Yukon XL 1500 4x4) when I turned on my blinker it would turn on the hazard lights.  It started at first with the only the right and then switched to the left blinker.  This is a pretty easy fix.  It is located on the back side of the fuse block underneath the steering wheel.  You have to remove the trim around the speedometer and then remove the plastic panel under the steering wheel.  It will be on the left hand side.  I had to unclip the fuse block to move it forward a bit to get enough wiggle room to remove the old flasher module. It is in pretty snug but with enough wiggling it does come out. The original flasher has a different part number, but I think this is a very common problem and this part works perfect and seems to be the new replacement part.

2/23/11 - Update: Well, we recently used this in very bright sunlight, with the GPS placed on the dashboard. Unfortunately, the sunlight totally washed out the GPS screen, and since the angle of the mount is not adjustable, there wasn't anything I could do to make the screen easier to see. Had to keep the GPS balanced in the cupholder. It would have been great to have a few different angle adjustments to minimize this problem. I've dropped my rating down to 3 stars.___Original review - In California, until recently it was illegal to mount a GPS (or anything else) on the windshield. That meant that you either needed to affix a GPS mount to the dashboard, possibly marring the surface over time, or deal with the slipping and sliding of a loose unit as you drove. I was in the latter camp, and ended up putting the GPS in the cup holder more often than not, occasionally picking it up to make sure I was heading in the right direction.I actually spent quite a bit of time looking for solutions to this problem. Believe it or not, no one seemed to make a non-adhesive GPS mount for the dashboard. I tried a beanbag for a while, but this was obviously not the best solution (people gave me funny looks when they saw a Beanie Baby on my dashboard).This mount by Heininger is exactly what I was looking for. It is a molded soft foam/latex frame which has a grippy bottom to keep everything in place on your dashboard, an angled design to keep the GPS at a good viewing angle, and an open back in case you have cords to attach to the GPS. Most importantly, once you get to your destination you can just throw the mount on the floor so that no one knows you have a GPS unit in your car.The only significant downside is that since there is technically nothing that is keeping your GPS unit in place except gravity, sudden turns or stops/starts can potentially cause the GPS unit to tumble out of the mount. As long as that doesn't fit your driving style, this mount should work well for you. Also, it is somewhat on the large side, which allows a widescreen GPS to fit nicely in it, but it may be too big for some smaller units, such as the TomTom One.

When buying LED fixtures for off road they should have a MINIMUM IP rating of 64,  RIGID INDUSTRIES I think are IP68,  these are very close at IP67:The two numbers in the IP67 rating code rating refer to:6 -    Dust Protected   ; Totally protected against dust ingress.; complete protection against contact7-    Immersion Protected   ; Protected against short periods of immersion in water.Ingress of water in harmful quantity shall not be possible when the enclosure is immersed in water under defined conditions of pressure and time (up to 1 m of submersion). Test duration: 30 minutes;  Immersion at depth of at least 1 m measured at bottom of device, and at least 15 cm measured at top of deviceSo unless your mounting these to your underwater submarine they should do just fine under normal, and by normal I mean severe off road, conditions.  Odds are if these LED's stop working because of water damage you'll probably be getting a new vehicle too.  God help anybody who cuts me off at night now!

I installed a pair of westin tubes almost 10 years ago.  After they rusted off, I got the aluminum sure step and this installation kit.  Probably the worst instructions I have ever seen.  Seriously, how hard is it to write some decent instructions. I could spend 10 minutes and write a better set of instructions.  After you get one side done, you figure it out.  The worst offense is that the brackets aren't engineered to fit correctly.  The bracket will bend the lower lip of the sheet metal as you tighten down the bolts.  It should have been at 90 degrees, but it is at about 80 degrees so the thin metal is stressed.  The bolts are barely big enough to get threaded, because of the incorrectly engineered bracket.  Once you finally get it threaded, it starts to bend the metal out.  Like the other poster mentioned, the self tapping screws are barely long enough and you have to be very delicate while drilling and set the clutch on the drill low so you don't drill out the hole completely like I did on my first hole.  I'm not convinced it will hold.  I may tack weld the brackets on if it gets loose.  I'm not thrilled about drilling holes in my truck.  There are plenty of factory holes and options that should have been utilized.  I wish I had gone with a different option/brand.  With stressed metal and questionable self tapped screws, not sure how long this will last.  I'm pretty sure I will need to weld these on at some point, if I don't just rip them off and start with a different brand.  This is on a 2001 F150 supercrew.

I purchased these Monroe quick-struts 2 1/2 years ago to replace a broken coil spring on my wife's 02 Focus (a common problem for that vintage Focus, thanks Ford). They were ideal for my situation because I got the whole spring/strut assembly for about what I would have paid for just springs. As a bonus, I didn't have to mess around with compressing the springs, as it was just a matter of bolting the new assembly into place. They were an exact replacement fit and they ride the same as the stock spring/struts (note: the car seemed to ride 'higher' for a few months, but the springs have since settled in). I would have reviewed them earlier but after installing them, I began hearing faint suspension related noises and held off until I tracked down the source. That turned out to be a failing motor mount (again, thanks Ford). Long story short, I completely forgot to review these struts. So with the hindsight of 2 1/2 years and 28,000 miles, I can report they are still working beautifully. No leaks at the struts, springs are in good shape, and an overall stock like handling suspension.

I read the negative review from a few years ago, and still thought to myself, they cant be that bad.  I drive a lowered civic, with aftermarket header and exhaust.  I'm use to a rough and loud ride, i figured these mounts cant make that much of a difference, its not like I'm use to driving a Cadillac, Wow was I wrong. After two weeks, i pulled these out today and installed new regular rubber mounts.Good:  these inserts fit perfectly into the stock mounts, even though one of my mounts was completely torn into two pieces. They are easy to install and fit securely into the mounts. They are a good product.Bad: These inserts basically turn your mounts into solid mounts. Every Vibration from the engine transferred directly to the cars body.  This isnt to bad at cruising speed, but was terrible at idle.  At stoplights, my front bumper rattled, the steering wheel shook, Sunroof cover rattled, the change in my center console danced around, etc...  On top of that there was a heavy drone inside the car, from the lack of sound deadening, coupled with the vibration.Opinion:  If you need solid mounts for a high power car/race car, and you dont care about excessive noise, these are perfect for you.  If you need new mounts for the car you drive everyday, spend the money and get new rubber mounts, you will be much happier.

I recently purchased a 2001 Chevy Suburban 1500 LS, 2 wheel drive.  When I got the vehicle home, I found several minor problems I needed to fix.  One of these problems was that the side power and heated rear view mirrors would move up, but not down, left, or right.  The passenger side mirror was broken, and was replaced, but the remote control would not function except to move the mirrors up.I looked here and found this switch.  I was encouraged because in appearance it was an almost perfect match for the switch I needed to replace.  The only difference was that my existing switch had black buttons, and this one was grey.  When I attemtped to order it, the drop down menus to check compatability appeared at the top of the page, asking for year, make, and model of the vehicle.  When that information was entered, the system advised that this switch would not fit my vehicle.  None of the other switches shown were even close in appearance.  I took a chance and ordered the switch anyway.  It arrived today, and except for color was an exact match of my exisitng switch.  It took less than 5 minutes to exchange the switches, and the mirrors worked perfectly.  I suggest that the compatability feature be looked at, and readjusted.  According to the system, this was not the proper switch for my vehicle, when in fact, it was.

works great. 09 silverado had NO oil pressure on the guage, STOP engine light came on. On the 5.3 litre GM engines, BEWARE there is an oil filter screen directly below this sensor.  REMOVE IT and throw it away.  It is meant to filter oil before the sensor , but mine plugged and i cleaned it a yr ago with carb cleaner, but plugged again. I removed the screen filter with a pick, and installed the sensor approx 6 months ago--still works fine. Filters havent been around under the sensors for 50 yrs but im sure that its there for a reason.....but i was tired of dealing with it.  Sensor can be installed without removing intake plenum, just use a socket and a u-joint swivel and you can access the sensor- its a 30 min job.....i can do it in 5 min now that i know how to do it. good luck. remove that oil filter screen under the sensor!!

Fit perfect but you have to drill the speaker rivets out of the old one and rivet it to the new one. I think that is just a VW flaw, among many others.
The installation of this component was very smooth and easy.  It looks like a more robust design than the OEM part.  It works terrifically well and may be better than the original.

I just finished installing this part.  While it may be as good as original, I can't rate it any better for the following reasons:  As other reviewers noted, it is different from original, there are NO instructions, and it is missing parts (2 nuts as mentioned in other reviews).  Some may be smarter or luckier than me, but I found it to be a royal pain to figure out correct angle/installation.  As for the references to YouTube instructions, from what I found (and I looked) there are no videos that cover the most difficult part of job: how to fit in a part that looks considerably different from the one you just removed.  For those who are where I was 2 hours ago:- Get the 2 nuts (10 mm) before you try to install new part.- Attach the arm (to left) with the protruding bolts through door w/ new nuts.- Once this is in place, it may be easier to figure out how to attach part (it DOES fit).- When in place properly, the motor should sit in upper right corner, pointing straight up,  if you are looking at it straight on (as if you could see through the door panel); if you look down from above, you see the cylinder shape of top of motor).- The four original bolts (in rectangular pattern) will go in place once it is sitting properly.- You will have 3 extra bolts from original that aren't needed .Good luck.
works great fit perfect ,i installed it according to the video on youtube and it worked perfectly,i highly recommend this

Easy to install! Worked great! Took about 40 minutes to get installed. A little slower than the other windows but I never use the back windows so its not a big deal. This will fix your window if it is sliding down by itself and is loose.

Installed somewhat easily.  Did not line up with window clamps correctly so I had to put it in crooked to get the window to raise and lower smoothly.  I was OK with this because once I got it installed and working correctly it worked very well.  That is until today.  Less than 2 months after I installed it it completely quite working.  Worst off it came down fine but would not go back up.  I had to drive all the way home with the window down on a cold rainy day.  I am not happy one bit with this item.  Please do not make the mistake I did and be tempted by the cheap price tag.  Just do a search for Bavarian auto sport in your favorite search engine, and buy theirs.  You will save yourself much time and a little money.
Easy install, works great. Very inexpensively priced; beats the heck out of going to the Cadillac dealership and getting bent over the parts counter.

some confusion with instructions, took me 4 hrs to remove and install, definitely need panel clips for reassembly, but it worked the 1st time!  now that i have completed, probably could do in less than 2 hrs to do this.

I installed this on my '91 Camaro. It is identical to the original.  Fitment was perfect, it functions properly, and actually raises and lowers the window faster than the original motor ever did.  When the other side burns out I'll be buying the same one.

My '01 Grand Cherokee window regulator went out in the middle of a snow storm! Ug.  So I went to the dealership and the quoted me $350 to replace the regulator!  The part from the dealer is over $200!  Then I found it here on Amazon for $57!!  SOLD!  So I purchased the regulator, and had it replaced and working again in around 45 minutes by doing it myself.  Was an easy replacement.  I would highly recommend this product!I gave 4 stars as there were no instructions, but once you get the door panel off it's easy to see how it goes in (by looking at the one already in there).  Also there are online help guides for Jeep window regulator replacements.  I don't think power window motors were ever very strong for the Jeep.  I have a dealer installed one on the drivers side, and the Amazon/self installed one on the right, and both motors sound weak.  However, since I have experience with the expensive and lesser expensive replacements, I hands down recommend the Amazon replacement.This is a great product that will save you hundreds! :)

I ordered the regulator to replace the one in my 2001 Chevy Silverado passengers door. The part arrived just as promised by Amazon. Opening the box I found the regulator, a piece of paper with information type on it describing the possible changes from the OEM part.  A small plastic bag with two nuts and a bolt in it. I removed the door panel. Taped the window and removed all the bolts. Removed the old regulator. Just as I figured the control cable had rusted and broken. I compared the new one to the OEM. On the bottom of the regulator where there was two bolts, there are welded studs on the new one.. Also, a support bracket mid way on the right side of the part is not present on the new one. It installed with ease. Studs lined up, all bolts lined up with no problems. Window clamps appeared to be the same as the OEM and tightened to the glass. Powered up and a few test runs all appeared to be fine. Time will tell.The paper work explained the difference of the OEM and the replacement with pictures, its a copy, but readable.I hope the missing support on the right side of the frame does not cause any problem later but time will tell. The paper work shows a picture and explains the missing point of contact.If you want to review the removal/installation of the door regulator, there's lots of videos online to show you the proper way to repair your regulator.The up/down speed appeared normal and non-laboredThis is an easy repair for the mechanically challenged.It took about an hour or so. Most of that was taking my time and removing the door panel, plastic and wire's and reinstalling them. Take your time and all will work out for this product.The part was priced anywhere from $40.00 to $60.00 dollars cheaper then I found at Auto Zone or Advanced Auto. These are the two parts places around me.I'll update if any problem with it, but so far so good...I HOPE to get years out of it.

This unit saved me a couple hundred bucks which my former mechanic wanted to charge me.  He had supposedly fixed it a year prior and then the window regulator busted again!  Thanks to my research on Amazon, I found this one, purchased it, went to YouTube to look at tutorial videos, and did it myself.  My cousin helped out too. We figured it out.  Wasn't too hard to install.  Thank you Amazon!!!!!!!Long live Amazaon!!!!!!!
Item arrived as described.  Was installed in less than an hour.  This was an easy purchase.  Description made it possible to assure we were getting the correct part for our vehicle.Thank you.
Fit is slightly off, but with a little effort it goes right together. Worked for about a week.  Won't not recommend.

I was searching for a good name brand regulator, and i ended up buying this crap.... the brackets didnt even fit my 2003 honda lx complete waste of MY money!! Please dont buy from them !!!Dorman 741-306 Honda Accord Front Driver Side Power Window Regulator with Motor
I bought this to replace the rear passenger door on my 1996 Camry 3.0. The fit is perfect, and works great. It's made in Tawain, so it's a better quality than those made in China.
Installed on my 2000 Harley Davidson FXST over two weeks ago. It was easy to install and works as described.The lifetime warranty is a great added value!!!!!
Bit of a pain to install but saved a lot of hard earned dinero.  Fast shipment, good quality.  Replaced them on a 2002 ford focus.

The original power window mechanism was giving me fits for some time, it worked about half the time but you never knew if it would be raining.  I found a You Tube Video that made it look pretty easy so I being reasonably handy gave it a try.  The video was not as clear in the descriptions as it could have been, I think the guy did it several times before making his video and along the way he left out some of the little things that would have clarified the directions.  These being the things that after the second time must have seemed insignificant to him, but not to me on my first time.I ordered this Dorman part and when it arrived I rounded up a friend to pass tools and hold stuff and to be ready with the bandages.The job was easy once I went over what I was seeing 3 or 4 times, I may have been better off without the video, but it did provide a tool list and some insight.Total time about 1 hr, no damage, no blood....well a little bit, there are a lot of burrs, be careful.The Dorman part works better than the OEM part and now I am going to do the Passenger door, just need that part number now.If you are a 3 or better on a 10 point mechanic scale, go for it.
Fit perfectly in my 2001 chevy suburban 3/4 ton . Installed inless than half an hour start to finish. As ling as it lasts it was well worth it. Saved about 90 dollars from a shop doing it.
Very easy to install in 2004 Kia Sedona.  Exactly the same as the original.  Amazon had this for about $60 less than any local auto parts store.

Needing to get it repaired ASAP I contacted and received a quote from our local Chevrolet dealership. After being blown away by what they wanted to charge I decided to repair this myself. Should any of the other regulators or motors experience a failure I will head right back to AMAZON to place another order.

This pump is priced very well, ships fast and works great. Installed with a breeze on a 1998 Toyota Corolla. The pump is a good quality product and comes with the rubber grommet which is crucial in order to prevent leaks, Overall very satisfied with the product.

I ordered the Mopar Windshield Wiper Spray Nozzles for a Mazda3 and they fit perfectly. The Amazon online vehicle verification confirmed that these would fit my vehicle, which was VERY helpful. These sprayers are exactly what I wanted for my car.

Perfect fit for my 1993 WJ. Had to apply a little silicone grease to the guide block so the tab on the new wiper would slide over the block and into the proper  #34;off #34; position.

I bought a pair of these to replace the disintegrating OEM blades on a 2006 E91 BMW 325xi. Installation wasn't the easiest, as BMW, in its infinite complicating wisdom, uses a special pin mount instead of the usual U-hook. Attachment involved removing a piece from the blade mount, and forcing the slightly-too-small pin hole on the blade onto the slightly-too-large pin on the wiper arm. (There are two pin holes on the wiper mount: a little too small, and way too large.)Note that these blades are reversible on their mounts, to match the curvature of your windshield. The blade carrier separates from the piece that attaches to the wiper arm, and can be reattached facing either left or right. Until I figured this out, the left blade kept a triangle of windshield directly in front of the driver's face un-wiped. I'm guessing that this is probably in the manual, so do read it.As with other Rain-X blades I've installed on other cars, these wipe with the best.
Fit perfectly and was extremely easy to install. It has seen much rain and snow and is still performing well.

Love the Bosch wiper blades. The Evolution series are the best, as they have a cap that swings down and covers the entire insertion area of the wiper. Makes removing the wiper, later on, much easier, because the cap keeps dirt etc. out of the wiper to wiper arm connection area. Unfortunately, these do not fit the rear window of the Subaru Forester 2005, as Amazon's car part finder suggested. The size of the blade is correct, but the connector is wrong.The blade needs to have a large round plastic dowel across the middle of the insertion area, so that the dowel swings up into place on the car's wiper connector arm. The rear window of the 2005 Subaru Forester does not have the standard   push it on the hook of the connector arm   setup. The Advantage series is the same as the Evolution series minus the protection cap, so these should be an excellent blade overall.

Unfortunately for me these are one of the only 2 brands that make a replacement wiper blades for my 2006 Toyota Avalon. After only a few months they wore out too. Plus they were a pain in the ads to change! I have had better luck with the cheap Walmart brand wipers than these. I was very disappointed. Won't be buying this brand again, I will spend the extra cash on the rain-x brand next time!

Exact fit. Better than paying twice the amount at the dealership. Couldnt find wipera at any auto parts store in my local area.
I was very happy to find a high-quality rear wiper blade for my 2007 Jeep Wrangler Rubicon. The installation was a snap ONCE you know the secret to proper installation.

These have to be the best wiper blades on the market. They were super easy to install by myself, and I am girly-girl.  Didn't even break a nail!

I bought these on sale, not knowing anything about them. I doubt I'll want to go back to any other blade now - they have lasted longer, and been more efficient than any previous blade I've used. This is an exact fit (no pun intended) replacement for the Subaru Outback rear wiper. I can not vouch for quality of durability, I just installed it, but at least installation was quick and easy.
Hard to find these in our area. These fit our Subaru Forester perfectly. They were shipped promptly after we placed the order.

My car uses the 20A on the passenger side and the 26A on the drivers side.This blade is easy to install, and that's half the battle. Before you order from Amazon, be sure to use the pop-up link to find the proper size for your vehicle. The blades come in both A and B sizes and different lengths. Some vehicles take different lengths for each side of the wind-shield. My Ford Edge takes the 26 A and the 20A.  I did not see a size listed on the website for the rear window wiper.I went to the Bosch web site before installing and they have a wonderful, helpful video about installation. Just search it under   wiper blades   on their site. Lots of helpful information there, for someone who never had to change their old blades. The packaging was simple to open after seeing the video. No need for box cutters or scissors like some over packaged goods.Another helpful hint from the video is to place a towel on the windshield in case the blade snaps out of your hand. (prevent a cracked windshield). You are also told the some vehicles require the blade to be in a vertical position before replacing, so sit in the car and turn on the wiper until it is upright. I know it sounds simple to you mechanical types, but tips like these mean a lot to those of us who were used to Service Stations actually giving service and when the local gas station attendant would check your wipers if asked.This is a good product, works well and is easy to do it yourself.

These blades are SUPER easy to install, and they work just as well as the blades that came on the car from new.Living in FL the sun eats the rubber on wipers pretty quickly, so I am expecting to replace blades several times throughout the year - I am glad to have found these much cheaper than the OEM ones, that work just as well (so far at least). No complaints, would buy again.

I order 3 blades total for my Subaru wagon, and I snapped each of them on without any trouble at all, maybe a minute or so for each one once I remembered how to remove the old ones! (I didn't need any adapters that come in the packaging, making it even easier)  The quality is fine; they certainly don't look or feel as nice as the Bosch wipers I have on my wife's Jetta, but for my old station wagon, for this price, they are fantastic.  I've only had a chance to use them a few times since I got them, so I can't comment on durability yet.

First, these blades are priced on the economical side so you will not get the sleek look of an expensive blade.  Personally, that is not something that matters to me, I am more concerned with performance and ease of installation.  I replaced my Altima's worn blades with this 17 #34; blade and a 28 #34; blade from this series. I was very happy with the 28 #34; blade but found performance of the 17 #34; blade to be just ok.First, installation was pretty simple.  I am not mechanical but I replaced both blades in about 5 minutes. However, the 17 #34; blades did not seem to have enough tension to lie flat on the windshield and left a lot of streaking where the last four inches of the blade met the glass.  I bent the blade a bit and that helped but there was still some streaking.  Not a lot but this is not an issue I've had with other 17 #34; replacement blades.  This is often a problem with the 28 #34; blades. Oddly, the 28 #34; companion blade worked very well! No streaking for that one. So, ok performance but nothing fantastic.
The item did not fit my BMW x3 in spite of having double checked the fit before buying it. The return date had expired so I have some more garbage in garage.

This wiper was easy to install on my husband's '09 Chevy Colorado and it fit perfectly. Immediately my husband noticed that the curved shape of the wiper puts a strong, even pressure down on the windshield and does a noticeably better job of wiping then the previous wipers. I should also point out that these wipers are noise free. We're very pleased with the performance and highly recommend this high quality wiper.

Agreeing with some critiques, the part that hooks onto the wiper arm is very bulky and is an eyesore.  The blade itself is low profile (as is with the new curved, steel-scaffolding-less wipers) but it is completely offset by the ugly plastic hump that joins the blade to the arm.  I was able to modify it to make it look far better than what it originally came as.  Be warned though that the stated lengths may not have the same exact proportions as the OEM-type wiper blades.  Some customers stated that the wipers are too short in some areas where it leaves a larger triangle left in the middle or they are too long that the blades nick eachother while being operated.  These are still good wipers with some shortcomings, thankfully of which did not affect me.Tips, I keep an older set of wipers on my car in the summertime because I may rarely use them.  I keep these on in the wintertime just because they are a bit pricier and don't want them to wear out so soon.  The older OEM style wipers can be refilled with just the rubber piece.  Once the Valeo ones go bad, you have to purchase the whole blade.  Summertime conditions can dry out and wear the rubber much faster.  At least the cold and perhaps wetter winter seasons can keep the rubber edges from going bad.
Me and my wife love it. It was the first time changing wiper my self andIt was easy to install.

I have a 2008 Mercury Milan and purchased sizes 19   and 24  . The sizes were fine, trying to install them is another story.  I had all kinds of difficulty trying to install the little clip piece (holds them in place once they're on the hook).  I've installed wiper blades before so I thought I knew what to expect...Not only was the installation hard, but they only cleaned half of the windshield.  I have no idea why that is, but they are being returned and I have already purchased some good Rain-X wipers.These sounded so promising...

In the middle of my windshield view where the blade attaches to the holder it leaves a 2   streak. I am NOT at all happy with these blades. This is a great wiper and fits all 2007 VW rabbits very easy to install. Couldn't get any simpler. Nice replacement
Works great, no streaks. You also get a towelette with silicon to treat the windshield.
the spoiler on this makes it great for the Crossfire.  It does a fine job of wiping the windshield and the spolier clears moisture away.

These are the best wipers blades I have ever purchased. Easy to connect, very quiet (no noise at all), no streaks at all. These lasts a long time. New England weather, snow, and ice, it does a great job.Sure, it's ugly, and looks like something from 1980's, but it works great, and lasts a long time.I'd recommend this to anybody. It works without any fluff. I've tried a lot of other brands, and I do have to say, it's close to Rain-X wipers in performance.

Bought this for my 2011 Chevy Traverse and it doesn't fit under the rear wiper blade cover. The website said that it would fit my car and when I got it, it didn't fit at all. Customer Service was very helpful and sent me a return label for free shipping. Nothing wrong with product.

Bought this for my wife's Yaris, just to try it out. I had installed Bosch wipers, but they started to fall apart after about 9 months. The Rain-X Latitude is quite unique. It is pre-curved and basically one piece. The curved blade is part of a curved frame that simply attaches to the wiper arm.Installation took about a minute. The hardest part was getting the Rain-X blade out of the package. Sprayed some Rain-x water repellent on the windshield after installing this (and a slightly different Rain-X blade for the passenger side -- smaller and not available in the Latitude series). The results were great. The blades moved across the windshield glass perfectly. No gaps, no streaks, no noise. I think the graphite coating on the Latitude makes a big difference. If they hold up as I'm pretty sure they will, these are my go to brand from here on out. Very satisfied.
They snap in easily and don't seem to fade after a year of sun.  I wouldn't recommend these for snow, but they're great for rain.
The blade snaps on easily.  The blade is slightly bent so it is snug against the windshield.  The wife says it works great!
Blades were not an exact fit for my VW Jetta TDi. These have a larger connection point.
True to OE and even have KIA on the package. Only OE wipers will work for the back wiper of a Kia Sedona.
it works but is about 1/4   too long. just slightly longer than the orginal.also, the rubber boot over the entire wiper does tear easy.
Finally, someone sells a direct-fit replacement for the rear blade on my '05 Pathfinder.Simple install. Does exactly what i need it to. Decent price too.
This wiper blade does not fit my vehicle as stated. The notches that secure the blade ended up breaking off.  Won't buy Valeo again.  Just buy OEM to save on a potential fitment issue.

I found it hard to get a replacement rear wiper for my 2008 Mazda 3 5 door. I read some other reviews for another brand that didn't fit correctly.The Valeo fits good. It installs in 10 seconds. It works fine.

Instead of running off to a Honda dealer parts dept and paying big bucks for the privelidge, I bought this item through Amazon instead. Easily fits well on my Honda. Hasn't been out in the rain yet so I don't know if it'll fly off in some direction or other. But appears to be quite a good solid fit for the rear wiper assembly. Only difference is it's 14 inches long and the origional is 15   long. I gave the product 5 stars because I'm fairly certain it'll work well. Trico wipers have been around for a long time and have a good reputation.

This is the first wiper of this type that I have used (non-hinged frame type) and I have to say that I am impressed.  Usually at highway speeds, my regular wipers start to lift a bit or do not maintain full contact with the windshield, but these low profile wipers keep full contact along the full length, for a clear windshield.  There was no squeak or stutter at any time, even in light rain or when using washer fluid, and they were able to keep up with a full-on heavy rain, which some wipers do not seem to be able to do.  This 20a wiper fits the passenger side of a 2009 Sonata among others (use a 24a for the drivers side of the 2009 Sonata), and works as good or better than any other wiper I have tried so far.  Installation was a snap, just following the directions/diagrams on the back of the package.  I do not live in an area with snow or ice, so I cannot on this wiper in   winter   conditions.
it fit Easley once you know how to change it, there is no instruction with it so I had to go online and see a video on YouTube, you will need to see that before you try to change it
