My 2002 Toyota highlander needed a new rear blade.  The OEM blade has a very unusual shape where the arm connects to the shaft.  I first ordered a cheaper Anco blade, but it did not fit, even though both the Anco and Amazon web pages showed it would fit.  I then tried this one, and it fit just fine on my 2002 Highlander, and it looks like it would work for my 09 highlander also.

Took about 2 minutes for each blade to remove and replace with new ones.  These come with the frame and not just the blades. The original frames fade in the sun and can use replacing every 30-50k miles.  Watch out...the Camry takes two different sizes one for the driver side and second for the passenger side.

First of all, all of the reviewers that gave these a negative review before me are all nuts. I've been using these for around a week or so now, and they are by far the best wiper blades you can buy (if you can really get excited about wiper blades). They are very sturdy, hug the windshield smoothly and evenly, and create a streak-free wipe every time, no matter how hard it rains. I have yet to test these in the winter, but with their frame-less design, I doubt these will under-preform. The only reasons I would believe some people don't like these are because those people are either cheap (These are about double the cost of regular blades, but are definitely worth it) or they don't use the Rain-X Windshield Treatment in addition to these. Like with Rain-X Washer Fluid, even though it doesn't mention this on the bottle, if you don't use the Rain-X Treatment along with it, it will make your windshield even dirtier after using it. It wasn't until I used the Rain-X Treatment along with the Washer Fluid until the product worked like a charm. The Rain-X Windshield Treatment does an awesome job at increasing visibility during showers, so it's a good thing to use anyways. If you're looking to get new blades, these are the best you can get, and will produce much better results than standard wiper blades.

This replacement blade is way superior to the standard replacement from BMW BUT the cover for the blade joint on the BMW doesn't quite fit over the entire hinge.  I hope it is a minor point and the cover doesn't come off but so far so good.

OK, I don't understand why, but several times now my reviews have been dropped by Amazon... So, here we go again.I wouldn't have known about this company/wiper if it hadn't been offered in Vine. I relied on the Amazon's recommendation engine to find the right size for my BMW 323i.  It turns out the driver side recommended blade is 2   shorter than the OEM blades.  They still work, however, but I am sure a portion of my windshield is now missing coverage.  Can't comment on the actual functionality of the product yet, as we only had one storm so far.Update:  Just had some decent rain storm in Calif.  These blades performed fine when working.  BUT ...1) Driver's side is clearly too short, adn about 1.5   patch in the middle of my windshield is not covered.  No big deal practically, but annoying.2) When driving fast on the freeway, there was one time, maybe because of heavy wind, the driver side wiper actually lifted - as in, not touching the glass.  This happened on one side.  When compared to the OEM blade, the OEM frame is a lot heavier, and has a contraption that seems like an airfoil.  Maybe this is why.  Compared to OEM blade, Anco seems light weight.  Overall, can't say I would recommend these for my car (BMW).

I'm comparing this to a   premium   Michelin wiper blade I had installed previously on my Civic, which I had purchased at the local Wal*Mart, and I think it holds up quite nicely. First of all, they both have a bracketless construction which prevents chunks of ice from getting stuck between the arms which would otherwise cause the wiper to become ineffective. Come blizzard time here in New England, that will be much appreciated.  This wiper installed more easily than the Michelin; the default mounting bracket worked perfectly and there was only one way--the correct way--to snap the blade onto my wiper arm. In addition, the mounting bracket is somewhat closed to the elements, and should prevent ice and other foreign objects from getting lodged there.So, I would characterize this wiper as well and thoughtfully constructed.[Update: wiper failed when the blade shredded after 2,5 years of service, pretty good as these things go.]As for the breast cancer awareness ribbon logo, it is clearly visible to the driver. I don't know what to think about that. My dear sister is a breast cancer survivor, and the disease has cost me in emotional pain; maybe I don't want to be reminded of that pain every day on the way to work.
I went to the dealer for a new rear wiper, they had to order it and it was $32 bucks! I declined and ordered this one.  Easy peasy done.  Fits perfect. Could not have been easier!  Do it!

Have to wait for rain, but as best I can tell a good oem replacement refill for the 2009 Mazda 6, s model, 6 Cly. This is the second generation Mazda 6, and I believe model changed again in 2014.Finding the right refill can be a challenge. Local pep boys does not stock refills and wants you to get complete wiper arm, Napa had generic refill but they lacked the metal strips. The metal strips are what gives the blade its spring, which in turns allows its to form fit to the glass.I measured my old ones, and they were 8mm. Just like these. As there are wide, narrow, extra narrow, best to measure first.For what it's worth, parts search returned these,   45-240 and 46-180   for driver/passenger respectively, they also listed the trico   17-240 and 17-180  . Not sure what those would have done and not clear what the difference is.Install tip: follow directions. ;)Seriously, they are picture based directions that have 3 steps so not hard. The metal strips can fall out easily. The new refill should have plastic clips that keeps everything together. Leave the clips on, and as you insert the new refill they will be pushed to the end and come off.

I bought 2 pairs of these for use with a Ford and a Mazda. Both have narrow wipers of appropriate length and are supposed to be compatible with this product.The refills are just a tiny bit too wide (not more than 0.5mm or 1mm too wide) and that makes them 100% unusable. On the Ford, where I was lucky and I managed to squeeze the refills in it took FOREVER to get it right (I spent almost 30 minutes on the first wiper and about 15 on the second)On the Mazda, I just couldn't get it done. I had to use pliers to slightly widen the gap on the little metal pieces that are supposed to hold the refill just to get it through and ended up destroying my blades.I cannot think of a single good thing to say about this item!do yourself a favor and buy a different product.

A perfect fit in the oem frames on my 08 Frontier.  Have been through several storms and I'm very glad I bought these, light rain at highway speeds I don't even need to turn on the wipers. I would buy again if needed.
